    "source_url": "Wiesmann Roadster (study) at <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiesmann_GmbH\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"en:Wiesmann GmbH\">Wiesmann Sports Cars</a>, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D%C3%BClmen\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"en:Dülmen\">Dülmen</a>, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Rhine-Westphalia\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"en:North Rhine-Westphalia\">North Rhine-Westphalia</a>, Germany<br><small>Wiesmann is a German sports car manufacturer based in Dülmen, founded in 1988 by brothers Martin and Friedhelm Wiesmann. The company became known for its handcrafted, exclusive sports cars with a retro design.<br>Its cars are characterized by a combination of classic lines—long hood, short overhangs, curved fenders—and modern technology. The company logo, a gecko, stands for traction and road holding. Production took place in a striking factory with a gecko-shaped roof.<br>Technically, Wiesmann relied on powerful engines from <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BMW\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"en:BMW\">BMW</a>. Models such as the Roadster MF3, MF4, and MF5 offered powerful six- and V8 engines, rear-wheel drive, and a very direct driving experience. The vehicles were considered purist, light, and strongly driver-oriented—without superfluous comfort, but with a high-quality interior in leather and aluminum.<br>In 2013, Wiesmann filed for bankruptcy and was later reorganized under new ownership.</small>",
